title: For Trade:  LMT Defender 2000 AR-15 for your AN/PVS-14 or 7
postcontent:
What I WANT:
Gen 3 or better Night Vision System (NVS), like a PVS-14 / 7 or OPMOD, etc. It can be rail-mounted, helmet / binoc, or even handheld monocular (order of preference). I'm also open to something in FLIR / Thermal as well. Whatever it is, it needs to have some REAL life left in it, not some 10 year old, battle-scarred beater. For the right unit I'm willing to add boot. 

What I HAVE:
One of my AR's is a gorgeous LMT Defender 2000 that has had fewer that 500 rounds put through it (all top-shelf brass, no steel-case crap). I have a few high-end AR's but this is the only one that has been a virtual safe queen. There literally is not a single use mark on it, it looks brand new. It's an all-original LMT, purchased earlier this year, that I have tastefully upgraded with useful, high-end parts -- a Troy Battlesight rear flip-up BUIS (dead-on co-witness), a Troy Carbine-Length quad-rail, an ERGO grip, Spike's billet trigger guard, a Magul CTS buttstock and B.A.D. lever, a LaRue Tactical buffer tube and Tubb Precision spring, and an AIMPOINT PRO up top that co-witnesses with the Troy BUIS and standard front A2 sight post. I think I still have the original LMT box as well, but will have to confirm that.

At **today's** prices this rifle is easily over $2,000 to duplicate, using the best current street prices.

This isn't some cheap Rock River, Bushmaster, Windham Walmart rifle or a Frankenbuild. No, this is a beautiful rifle, and is ready to be YOUR go-to battle rifle. If you're interested feel free to email or call. I'm in Northeast Alabama, and I have my own 150-yard rifle range if you want to come by and give her a test-drive. Just bring your NVS along, and we can talk turkey.

I'm NOT interested in selling the rifle outright, unless you know someone who has a NVS and he's willing to do a 3-way deal.

Brendan -- (256) six 6 zero - one 5 six 6

title: For Sale:  (10) 10 Gauge Flares - White Star in Sealed Tuna Can
postcontent:
This is a rare factory sealed can of 10 gauge "white star" flare ammo that was made for the war effort by Rochester Fireworks Company in February 1944. However as the war was starting to wind down - some of this ammo went unused so it was repacked into sealed tuna cans (of 10 rounds each) by the manufacturer in October of 1945. Then some of these ended up finding their way to the surplus market at some point.

This is the correct flare ammo for all those Remington, H&R, and Sedgley flare pistols out there that are chambered for 10 gauge.

You can look, and look and look some more and may never find another sealed can of these flares. They are quite unusual & collectible. 

I obtained some of these in a blind box lot purchase at the estate sale of an old military collector who passed away.

Asking $100 for the sealed can. I see these same flares for sale from time to time on the gun auction sites and asking price is usually about $25 per round.

Pick them up in Brandon and you must be at least 18 to purchase.

p.s. As these flares are packed in a sealed can that has remained unopened since 1945 - I cannot speak to or guarantee their condition. However I feel reasonably sure they are all live and useable. They were canned about 18 months after they were manufactured and this particular can shows no visible signs of damage, tampering, or corrosion, and the fact is that it's in unbelievable shape for being over 68 years old.

title: For Sale:  **RARE** TOMMY GUN CARBINE BY EAGLE GUN COMPANY
postcontent:
Eagle Gun Company  Thompson style carbine. This is a rare weapon. It is an open bolt fired carbine. The Eagle Carbine was developed and manufactured in small numbers from 1964-68. The gun has iron sights (which were only used during the first year of production making this particular gun even harder to find than ones made during the next 3 years of production). As far as legality, This particular design was followed by the Spitfire, Commando and Apache Carbines which appeared in the early 1970's. The Spitfire's and Apache's were banned by the ATF and reclassified as "machine guns", in effect making this already rare Eagle Carbine the only legal version of this type of firearm.

Mass produced holsters do not have the detailed boning that custom holsters have which does not retain the handgun as well as custom holsters. If you have ever experienced a mass produced leather holster, you know that the leather becomes well-worked and soft within a month or so, but you don't have any of that with the High Noon. title: For Trade:  800 Rounds Federal HST .40S&W JHP
postcontent:
Best CCW Ammo you can buy!

For sale/trade is 100 rounds of Federal HST 155gr JHP for a .40S&W.
I do have more of this ammunition if you would like up to 800 rounds.

Federal released its Hydra-Shok line of ammunition to capture the law enforcement market years ago, and while it was a good round - it proved troublesome when going through barriers before reaching its target - clogging much of the time.

Federal corrected the problem by introducing a line known as HST, and it was tested extensively by the FBI upon its release in .40 caliber, and adopted as their ammunition after blowing the tests out of the water. This is currently the only ammunition I will carry as I feel like it is the only ammunition to hold a candle to the famous "Black Talon".

It's easy to find the much less desirable Hydra-Shok ammunition on the shelf, and many people are intrigued by the "post" inside the hollow point. If you do the research, and I suggest you do, you will find that HST is extremely tough to beat.

That's why HST has almost never (in my experience) been for sale on the shelves at your local gun shop - I have only ever found it online, for a premium price, and in small or limited quantities. I have recently switched to a different caliber for my preferred CCW and cannot find anywhere that sells HST in bulk, must less a place with a single box in stock right now.

I live in Puyallup, but will be willing to drive a reasonable distance to meet - or even ship if you want to pay for shipping. I will also be in Spokane for the holiday weekend and can meet there.

Take a look here for FBI Protocol test results on this ammunition
http://le.atk.com/ammunition/federal/handgun/details.aspx?id=567

postcontent: PICTURES ARE REPRESENTATIVE ONLY. WITH BLASER RAZ SIGHTS. THIS IS NOT SHOWN IN THE PICTURE. THE R93 LUXUS SPORTS ALL THE FEATURES OF THE BLASER R93 SYSTEM; STRAIGHT PULL BOLT , 360 DEGREE RADIAL BOLT LOCK UP; SEAR FREE TRIGGER MECHANISM; FREE FLOATING INTERCHANGABLE BARRELS AND THE SILENT THREE POINT SAFETY SYSTEM; RAPID SIMPLE TAKEDOWN; ALL OF THIS COMES HANDSOMELY PACKAGED WITH A TWO PIECE UPGRADED STOCK OF FIGURED HIGH GRADE TURKISH WALNUT WITH EBONY FOREND, ACCENTED BY ENGRAVED GAME SCENES ON THE SIDE PLATES. OVER 36 DIFFERENT CALIBERS CAN BE HAD. Incorporating innovations that raise the standards for quality and performance, the Blaser rifles mark the beginning of a revolution in bolt-action design. In fact, these rifles represent the first truly new concept in bolt-action rifle design since the bolt-action idea was first introduced. Foremost among its breakthrough features is its fast, smooth, straight pull bolt movement. Unlike conventional bolt actions, you operate the Blaser action by simply pulling the bolt to the rear and pushing it forward, with no lifting. Its faster, smoother and less likely to affect your aim for the next shot. Less obvious but equally remarkable is the Blaser's Radial Locking System (see details below). It's built around a radial bolt that expands 360? to make full, rigid contact right inside the barrel for a solid lock-up. Also contributing to the Blaser's performance are its patented sear-free trigger mechanism and completely free-floated barrel. Altogether, these design innovations result in a level of accuracy that no conventional bolt-action rifle can match. Dedicated to any single caliber, the Blaser R93 would rank among the best bolt-action rifles in the world. But the Blaser R93 rifles were engineered to allow for barrel and caliber interchangeability. Quick take-down and a replacement barrel and bolt head are all that's needed to provide maximum versatility in the Blaser R93. The technologically advanced Blaser Radial Locking System gives you five distinct benefits: 1) The bolt locks directly into the barrel, not into a receiver, so you get a full-length barrel in a rifle that's 4" shorter overall, 2) The frame receives minimum stress because the bolt locks directly into the barrel, making the Blaser lighter and easier to handle, 3) Radial lockup means that stress is distributed through a full 360? of contact, for greater system strength and durability, 4) Head space is precisely controlled because the bolt head locks directly into the barrel, and 5) The bolt head is free-floating, so it self-trues into a concentric position in the bore, relieving stress and assuring a higher degree of accuracy. There is no other rifle system with the versatility or pure shooting ability of the R93. Seventeen different standard and magnum calibers, including the new .300 Ultra Mag., ensure that there's a perfect choice for any hunting challenge. Due to its revolutionary straight-pull bolt and radial lock-up, the bolt mates directly to the barrel with full 360? locking contact for superior strength and rigidity. Because the R93's bolt locks directly into the barrel, the R93's frame receives minimum stress which allows the rifle to be both lighter and shorter, so it's easy to carry and quicker handling. The trigger is sear-free, and designed so the "creep" is eliminated. Let-off is crisp and precise. Scope mounts directly to the barrel, so that rifles can be easily broken down and reassembled without changing point-of-impact. Barrels are cold hammer forged and are machined to accept detachable scope mounts. They are free-floated, so that atmospheric changes won't affect your point-of-aim. The R93's straight-pull bolt is an engineering marvel and includes a safety which actually cocks/decocks the firing mechanism. There's even a rubber bumper built into the magazine well to protect bullet tips from recoil damage. The list is endless.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1895 TAKEDOWN - 405 W.C.F. - EXCELLENT
postcontent: Superb Winchester Model 1895 mfg. in 1912 - Serial #649xx. The action is incredibly tight & locks up beautifully.  Bore is great with deep rifling - stock and forearm are in excellent condition.  This Takedown model has been in our collection for over 50 years, rarely fired, & reflects the most sought after model.  Bluing was refinished prior to our acquisition, markings remain crystal clear, all wood & hardware are original, & the Lyman case sight is flawless.  The Model 1895 was the first Winchester rifle to feature a box magazine located underneath the action instead of the tubular magazine design.  The 1895 was also the last of the lever action rifles to be designed by John Browning.  The model 1895 in .405 W.C.F. is most commonly associated with former President Theodore Roosevelt, who praised the model in his book African Game Trails, famously referring to it as his "medicine gun" for lions.

title: Want To Buy:  Your WWII Items
postcontent:
Hello. I am a local WW2 collector. I have a passion for collecting primarily German items from the Word War 2 era.

So few of our US vets are still around to see the appreciation that still exists for their service to our country and in my own small way, I am trying to preserve that history by learning and collecting authentic items from that time period. 

If your father, grandfather, uncle or anyone else you know left you with any German items from WWII, I would like to buy them at a fair price if you're willing to sell them. I'm also happy to help you understand, identify and put a current value on your items with no strings attached. 

Items that interest me include flags, banners, daggers, knives, hitler youth items, armbands, helmets, hats, field equipment, belt buckles, patches, insignias, medals, awards, swords, ss, sa, nskk, Luftwaffe, kriegsmarine
